Explanation:

We use two queues, front_queue and rear_queue, to implement a LIFO (last-in-first-out) stack. The push operation adds elements to the front of the front_queue, while pop and top operations remove elements from the rear_queue. The empty() function checks if both queues are empty.

The solution has a time complexity of O(1) for all operations, as the operations directly access elements from the queues without iterating through the stack. The space complexity is O(1) since we only use two queues. The energy implications are low, as the operations do not consume significant energy.

